Chapter 1: Reliability, Scalability, Maintainability

1. What is Reliability, Scalability, Maintainability
2. Reliability: 
    a. System will work even if anything goes wrong.
    b. Hardware Errors
    c. Software Errors
    d. Human Errors
    e. How to detect them while development, while maintenance and handle them.
3. Scalability:
    a. System will work or can be modified easily to work with increased load.
    b. Scalable up and scalable down
    c. Even if the scale up is needed or not for the system
    d. What is a load
    e. Latency and response time: 
        - latency is request waiting to be served and response time is actual time the user saw for the response
        - the 99th percentile latency is called the tail latency.
        - 95th 99th 99.9th percentiles for the latencies and response time
        - SLAs (external contract) and SLOs (internal objective) for the latnecies
    f. Scaling up (verticle) and scaling out (horizontal) (shared nothing)
4. Maintainability:
    a. System will be easy to run, understand and modify.
    b. most of the cost goes in maintenance instead of development
    c. operability: make systems running smoothly, make it easy for operations
    d. simplicity: make systems understandable easily, manage complexities easily
    e. evolvability: make systems modifiable easily.
5. Functional and Non-functional requirements
    a. the ablove reliability, scal;ability and maintainability are non functional requirements of the system
6. CAP theorem:
    a. Consistency: same response for same request irrespective of request time, server, location, etc.
    b. Availability: always a response for a request, irresepective of correctness or errors there will be some response.
    c. Partition Tolerance: system is working even if there is a partition.
    d. Theorem says there can only be two of the above at a time.
    e. In general network paritions are present in the system and if we want to make the system parition tolerant 
            i.e. system working even if there is a parition then we can sonly have either consistency or avialbility
    f. If system is both available and consistent then in case of partition, system won't be working (can't tolerate the parition)


